The following code gives me three width warnings where LHS is 1-bit and RHS is 4-bit.

```
module logical_operators(input wire [3:0] a,
                          input wire [3:0] b,
                          output wire y0,
                          output wire y1,
                          output wire y2);

  assign y0 = !a;
  assign y1 = (a && b);
  assign y2 = (a || b);

endmodule

```

I really appreciate the verilator lint errors, so I don't want to turn them off, but I'm curious if this is an issue with my understanding of verilog or verilator. I know verilog has some surprising characteristics, so is the right-hand-side actually 4-bits?

Is it recommended to write logical operators like this:

  assign y0 = !(|a);
  assign y1 = (|a && |b);
  assign y2 = (|a || |b);

Thanks for a great tool!

